To celebrate the end of another year filled with music, family and friends, we’re happy to be releasing a series of four limited edition camp flags made by our friends at @oxfordpennant. Featuring some of his favorite lyrics, the flags are based on Ray’s original sketches pictured in the last 3 slides. 

All four flags are available now in his store - orders placed by Friday Dec. 9th should ship in time for the holidays. Link in bio to shop now.

Join The Cabot Club at the Turquoise level of membership or higher to gain access to the presale, more info available on Ray’s website.
Tickets for The Cabot’s Big Night on April 28th with Ray and Lucinda Williams are on sale now through the link in bio!

Valentine’s Day is coming up next week! There’s still a handful of Ray’s limited edition camp flags available in his store if you’re looking to grab a little something for a loved one - link in bio to shop now.

So often, it seems, the songs that are most direct tend to overshadow those that are more subtle, more patient. 
 
My son Tobias, a filmmaker and visual artist @tobiaslamontagne and I have collaborated many times over the years to create everything from award-winning stop motion shorts to music videos.
 
During the next several weeks we will be sharing a series of vignettes, a combination of imagery and melodies from two decades of songwriting. 

Hope you enjoy, but…
Hey, no pressure. 

Ray

I can, and quite often do, go for months on end without picking up a guitar. I have always felt that the muse is a pure, childlike creativity that each of us possesses. In its innocence it is fearless; and you should be patient with it, and respect it. So, when a melody filters through and begins to tug on my sleeve and ask for my attention, I drop everything and I listen. In this way, every melody, every lyric, every song is a discovery, a gift. No other album represents this relationship with my own creativity more starkly than Ouroboros. When I listen to this album I can hear just how grateful I was to receive it. It comes through, softly, like a prayer. 
Ray

The Gossip in the Grain session is especially memorable for me for many reasons, although a full fifteen years have passed since those two weeks in Bath England at Peter Gabriels studio Real World. The day this song was recorded, producer Ethan Johns and I had had another of our quietly smoldering verbal punch-ups. Understand, both Ethan and I were much younger, equally intense and, most certainly, placing far too much weight on the importance of the work we were doing. Our disagreement led to Ethan leaving the studio. I remained with the engineer, sat down with my guitar and said “let’s just roll it” and got this take of Winter Birds. Listening to it now, I can hear the heavy emotions of the day in the performance. And I’m sending Ethan a big hug, back through the years. I hope he gets it. 

Ray

Every single word of this song is true.
Ray
Ray has loved seeing your setlists so far! If you haven't had a chance to make yours yet, you can still make one at the link in bio.

Smashing was one of the first songs I wrote in a batch of tunes that would become the Supernova album, songs that came about during a two year hiatus from touring and written while renting a small cottage for a week with my wife Sarah in a village on the coast of Maine. “Looking through the glass as the moon rolls over, church and steeple, hill and harbor, do you ever wonder what it is inside us? Do you ever wonder where it is inside us?” Clearly, I was still searching. But the crux of the tune is the line “I’ll be the one who stays”. My family tree is littered with the remains of broken relationships. Seems the one thing I did know, even in the midst of that dispirit time in my life, was that I wasn’t giving up on us. I wasn’t going anywhere. 
Ray
